The morning chirp of a bird or a frog's evening croak offers more than  
natural background noise. Researchers can use the sounds of rainforest  
species to measure the impact of climate change. Based on recordings from  
eco-acoustic monitoring systems, data science may enable more effective  
conservation efforts.

In this competition, you'll automate the detection of bird and frog species  
in tropical soundscape recordings. You'll work from limited, yet  
acoustically complex, training data that is rich in more than bird and frog  
noises. Expect to hear an insect or two, which your model ought to filter  
out.

Help enable early detection of the environmental impacts of humans,  
allowing for swift and effective conservation.
